Dan,<br><br>
Thanks for your reply. You are helping me to get closer to what I felt I was missing in my thoughts.<br><br>
You said:<br><br>
&quot;We NEVER hated the vets. We were simply frustrated that they SEEMINGLY gave-in, so readily, to authoritarianism!&quot;<br><br>
The point I would like to make is that at the core, the issue was not so much of content, but more of form.<br><br>
Let's consider my wellspring.<br><br>
Having been born into a military family with some military history and attitude on both sides, I was &quot;indoctrinated&quot; from a very early age to a certain set of values. Service in the military had a certain sense of obligation. <br><br>
Others joined the military for perhaps other reasons. I know many people who joined because it was their doorway to a better life and status.<br><br>
Still others had simply no other choice than it was the law. The draft was a grim reaper. <br><br>
We did not capitulate, but participated in that which we were required by the long history and precedent of this society. A certain amount of &quot;authoritarianism&quot; was expected and tolerated.  <br><br>
We would have probably taken the same path if there had been no Vietnam War.<br><br>
On the flip side, the protestors were portrayed to those of us in the military as a bunch of reckless far left society destroying drugged out whacko's who had nothing better to do than fullfill some form of cultural penance because their parents were filthy rich.<br><br>
I know that is not true for 99.999% of all the protestors. <br><br>
If there had been no Vietnam War, from what direction would you have come? <br><br>
Thanks. 
